[2024/05/03 12:00:00 GMT+0000] [00:08:30] Participant 36: I can read the newspaper, just so that we have an idea of what happened, essentially. 
[00:08:37] Participant 35: Okay. [00:08:40] Participant 36: The Perdition Sheriff's Office announced Monday that it has ruled the death of Old Scratch Tavern owner, Nicholas Webster, an accident. So, Nick Webster is the Tavern owner. According to the Sheriff, Webster fell to his death in the early hours of Saturday morning, likely minutes after leaving the Old Scratch Tavern. It was dark, and unfortunately Nick just lost his footing, McGinty said at a press conference Monday morning. A neighbour discovered Webster's remains at the bottom of Devil's Well, a local waterfall, early Saturday morning. So, yeah, time, early Saturday morning. This was not the first misfortune to befall Webster and his Tavern in recent months. In July, Webster told this paper, nothing valuable was stolen during a series of petty burglaries, but said he was taking measures to ensure that the incidents did not continue. Sheriff McGinty confirmed that no perpetrator was apprehended for the thefts. More recently, Webster had reported a series of small fires, and other disturbances at the bar. Official records show that Webster called Perdition emergency services ten times between September 1st and December 7th. Yeah, let's keep the dates in mind. Carmen Rojas, a bartender at Old Scratch, so Carmen is the bartender, and the person who's writing. 
[00:10:03] Participant 34: Uh-huh. [00:10:07] Participant 34: She said, Webster feared someone was out to get him, though she did not know who might have wanted to harm her employer. The circumstances of Webster's death led some residents, including Rojas, to speculate whether his fall might not have been accidental. However, Sheriff McGinty was adamant that those claims are groundless. Okay, yeah. I'm sure my deputy would have discovered signs of foul play, he said. We're looking at someone who was a little worked up, who'd had a drink or two, it's tragic, but accidents happen. Webster's widow, Cherie…is she one of the suspects, yes, she's one of the suspects…said in a statement, I have faith in the Sheriff's Office, and I'm so grateful for their help. Nick was the love of my life; I don't know what I'll do without him. Mrs Webster did not address whether Old Scratch Tavern will reopen, but Perdition's residents will surely miss their favourite neighbourhood barkeep. Carol Newar…Carol, is she one, no she's not…a member of the Perdition's billiards club said, Old Scratch's pool championship won't be the same without Nick cheering us on. Donna Goddard, a long term patron of Webster's bar – she's one of the suspects – said, it's heartbreaking, Nick made the best old-fashioned in town, and I know I won't be the only person having one in his honour tonight. Funeral service will be held on Sunday at 11 a.m. at Bob's Funeral Home, followed by a reception. Yeah, and on the back, there is some information about Devil's Well, which is where…
